WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.600
Thank you, everybody, for joining, and I know we just hit the top of the hour, so welcome

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:15.000
to the Data Science Hangout. I know it's a bunch of familiar faces here, but anybody

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.080
who's joining for the first time, welcome. This is an open space for the whole data science

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:26.959
community, current and aspiring data science leaders to really connect and chat about some

00:00:26.959 --> 00:00:33.040
of the more human centric questions around data science leadership. We really, I'm just

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:37.320
going to mute people if there's a little bit of background noise, but we really want to

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:44.320
create spaces where everybody can participate and hear from everyone. So you can jump in

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:49.599
live and ask questions, you can put questions in the chat. And we also have a Slido link

00:00:49.599 --> 00:00:55.119
where you can ask anonymous questions too. So if you don't want to be a part of the recording,

00:00:55.119 --> 00:00:59.840
it's a great way to ask questions too, because we will share this up to YouTube as well for

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:06.599
anybody who missed it. But with that, I'm so excited to be joined by my co host for

00:01:06.599 --> 00:01:13.440
today, Jarus Singh. Jarus is a Director of Quantitative Analysis at Pandora. And Jarus,

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:17.959
I'd love to turn it over to you and have you introduce yourself and maybe start off by

00:01:17.959 --> 00:01:21.360
sharing a bit about your team and the work that you do.

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:30.080
Yeah, thanks, Rachel. Thanks for having me today. Really excited for this. So I lead

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:36.080
a team of three. We're quantitative analysts. And what's a little unusual is that we're

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:41.919
embedded in a finance team. And as a quick aside, when I first joined, I was very skeptical

00:01:41.919 --> 00:01:47.639
of being on a data team sort of embedded in the finance org, just because they're not

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:52.440
historically known for, I think, putting as much emphasis on data or the right emphasis

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:59.559
on data relative to sort of other orgs that may have more of a history of doing so. But

00:01:59.559 --> 00:02:04.599
it's actually worked out really, really well for us. So, you know, the way I view the team

00:02:04.599 --> 00:02:09.479
is that we have three sort of pillars that we're responsible for. One is reporting. So

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:14.639
what happened? And this is all the metrics that Pandora cares about that informs its

00:02:14.639 --> 00:02:19.759
financial model. So it would be users. It would be how much people are listening. What

00:02:19.759 --> 00:02:23.559
platforms are they listening on? What are the demographics of listeners? All of these

00:02:23.559 --> 00:02:30.440
have impacts on what we pay for spitting the tracks or, you know, the revenue that we can

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:34.800
make against people when they're listening on the free tier from advertisements or, you

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:39.880
know, the propensity to join a trial and then eventually subscribe. So that's the first

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:45.360
pillar is reporting. Second is forecasting. What does the future hold? We do that using

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:51.119
a lot of R and we try to rely on algorithmic and automated techniques as best as possible,

00:02:51.119 --> 00:02:55.360
but realize that, like, they can't do everything for you. So there are times where, you know,

00:02:55.360 --> 00:03:00.080
you need sort of human in the loop style modeling where someone has to look at it and say, OK,

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:03.839
I'm getting information from this team saying they're going to change their strategy and

00:03:03.839 --> 00:03:08.039
we need to make sure that we're not relying entirely on an algorithm that is not aware

00:03:08.119 --> 00:03:13.479
of sort of that change that's coming. And then the last pillar, I'd say, is data driven

00:03:13.479 --> 00:03:18.679
decision making. So we have a wealth of information about our users. If we're going to go out

00:03:18.679 --> 00:03:25.679
and do marketing or special deals with, you know, it could be a telecom company or a device

00:03:25.679 --> 00:03:30.080
manufacturer, we want to understand the most we can about the sort of users they're going

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:36.720
to bring in or the deal terms so we can use our knowledge of Pandora's data to come up

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:40.880
with a very refined estimate of what we think would happen under those under those deals.

00:03:42.759 --> 00:03:48.119
Cool. I'm trying to think of myself as a Pandora user, like in the app itself. Is there

00:03:48.119 --> 00:03:53.279
something that maybe the data science team has worked on that I would see as a user

00:03:53.279 --> 00:04:00.880
directly? Yeah. So my team is mostly dealing with like business metrics, I would say. So

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.960
there's not a lot of stuff we've done where I'd be like, oh, I worked on that. It's more

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:09.399
like every time you go in and engage with the app, it's like we're trying to predict how

00:04:09.399 --> 00:04:12.960
much we think you're going to use it and sort of the potential you have towards the

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:18.239
business. LTV as well is important. But yeah, you know, we're not selecting the next song.

00:04:18.239 --> 00:04:23.040
So good to kind of level set for this discussion before I get questions about about that.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:30.959
Yeah. Thanks, Jairus, for the intro. While we're asking for a few questions from the

00:04:30.959 --> 00:04:36.239
audience and waiting for those to come in, I'd love to hear about something that you're

00:04:36.239 --> 00:04:42.079
most excited about in regards to data science as you look forward to 2022.

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:50.000
Yeah, I guess like generally in the space, what I'm seeing is and this is from sort of

00:04:51.559 --> 00:04:56.399
some data groups that I'm in and just reading blog posts is that data folks, I think they

00:04:56.399 --> 00:05:00.920
know they have a lot to offer to the table, but they're not always in the room where

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:05.359
decisions are being made and they're not always able to inform those decisions in the way

00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:10.799
that I think they can and should. And what I see is the space sort of maturing in that.

00:05:10.799 --> 00:05:15.920
Like, I personally believe that data folks are going to get more ownership over things

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:20.040
that sort of should be in their purview, but aren't necessarily at all companies.

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:25.040
Some companies are doing this very well where they're using data where data can help.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:27.839
But I think not all companies are on that stage of maturity.

00:05:27.839 --> 00:05:32.920
So I'm expecting sort of more maturity from the space where people are getting more

00:05:32.920 --> 00:05:37.119
sophisticated about using data when sort of applicable.

00:05:37.119 --> 00:05:41.760
And to throw out a company example that I've heard really great things about in the past

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:45.239
and seeing Hilary Parker talk for when she was there would be Stitch Fix.

00:05:45.239 --> 00:05:50.679
Right. So the way she kind of presented them is that anything that can be informed by like

00:05:50.679 --> 00:05:55.760
the data scientist skill set well or better than what you would get, you know, leaving

00:05:55.760 --> 00:06:01.559
that as someone else's decision who doesn't have a skill set that's being put in the data

00:06:01.559 --> 00:06:04.399
team's hands. So I thought that was a really cool way of framing it.

00:06:04.399 --> 00:06:06.920
And I think more companies are going to be moving that direction.

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:14.799
Awesome, thank you. I see Arafat just asked a question in the chat and asked that I read

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:18.600
it out loud, and so I just want to say if anybody uses the Zoom chat and you want me to

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:21.679
read it out loud, just put a little star at the end so we know.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:27.640
But Arafat asked, could you share some more detail about the project

00:06:28.839 --> 00:06:32.480
that you shared earlier or refer to a resource or book?

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:39.559
Yeah, of course. So Human in the Loop is sort of this framework

00:06:39.559 --> 00:06:45.320
that says you can rely on any automated system or algorithms

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:50.519
to generate some of a result, but ultimately a human has to be in the loop

00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:55.720
somewhere at some stage, right, verifying the output, changing it as necessary

00:06:55.720 --> 00:07:00.519
and is basically able to improve upon the system if it were a computer alone or a human

00:07:00.519 --> 00:07:02.880
alone. So I can give some examples of that.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:04.880
And another one's going to come from Stitch Fix.

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:09.640
I feel like I work there even though I don't, but they have some really cool use cases.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:14.959
So the first one I'll give is from our world, right, where we're using a lot of time series

00:07:14.959 --> 00:07:17.359
techniques to forecast the future.

00:07:17.559 --> 00:07:22.880
And the time series technique is if it's univariate, we'll just look at historical

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:25.200
data. How has this been trending?

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:26.720
What is expected seasonality?

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:28.480
And we'll extrapolate that forward.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:33.679
So that makes sense when the future state of the world is sort of structurally similar to

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:35.320
what we've experienced in the past.

00:07:35.559 --> 00:07:40.519
But if we were to make a change and it's an anticipated change, that's where the human has

00:07:40.519 --> 00:07:44.720
to get involved. So an example I'll give you is we were

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:51.480
growing a certain platform on the on the service, you know, pretty quickly over time,

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:53.359
and it looks like it was a predictable series.

00:07:53.559 --> 00:07:57.399
But we tried to make some changes to the user experience there that we thought would

00:07:57.399 --> 00:07:58.559
actually dampen growth.

00:07:58.559 --> 00:08:01.760
They would have an adverse effect on growth going forward.

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:04.679
Now, the model has no idea that that's happening, right?

00:08:04.679 --> 00:08:06.720
There was no way for us to sort of pass that in.

00:08:06.959 --> 00:08:12.119
So we create sort of what we would expect to happen under the old regime.

00:08:12.279 --> 00:08:15.040
And then we layered in assumptions we got about the new one.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:19.160
And sorry for being vague, but I shouldn't probably go into too much more detail.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:22.839
So that's where it's like you're accounting for the fact that the algorithm doesn't know this

00:08:22.839 --> 00:08:24.200
change is happening in the future.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:27.399
And you use an alternate set of data and assumptions to do that tweak.

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:32.039
A really cool stitch fix example I heard is when they're actually selecting clothes for

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:37.520
folks. So there's a lot of feedback that people can give on prior sets of clothes they've

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:42.039
gotten, which a computer may or may not be good at really understanding.

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:48.039
So if the NLP side of their business isn't fantastic, it may not realize like, OK, this

00:08:48.039 --> 00:08:53.200
person's OK getting pants, but like they still want some, but they don't want it always.

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:57.799
And a human can do a good job of saying, OK, maybe I should send pants in a kit every

00:08:57.799 --> 00:09:00.039
other kid or every every third or something.

00:09:00.599 --> 00:09:04.840
So it's an area at which you would not expect whatever algorithms you have to perform

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:09.799
well. A human has to intervene and and kind of adjust what you would get.

00:09:09.799 --> 00:09:12.359
And you get a better sort of outcome with that.

00:09:13.119 --> 00:09:17.280
In terms of resources, I'm not sure if it's addressed in this book, but it's one of our

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:22.000
favorites. It's by Rob Hendeman and it's on forecasting.

00:09:22.359 --> 00:09:25.200
If you go to Otex.org, it's actually available for free.

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:27.239
They're forecasting principles and practice.

00:09:27.919 --> 00:09:30.840
That's what my team relies on a lot for a lot of the work that we've done.

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:37.039
I think Tori maybe shared that book earlier as well.

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:37.760
Oh, gotcha.

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:39.280
One that's really helpful, too.

00:09:40.479 --> 00:09:45.159
That's interesting about Stitch Fix, too, because I use Stitch Fix and I am one of the

00:09:45.159 --> 00:09:50.760
people giving that feedback and they make it seem like it is a human interacting with

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:54.039
you on that. There was an anonymous question.

00:09:54.679 --> 00:09:56.159
Oh, sorry. You go ahead, Frank.

00:09:56.559 --> 00:10:00.880
Thanks, Rachel. I'm going to pop in and just add another recommendation from a previous

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:05.640
one of our calls who Paul from Kentucky, I forget his last name.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:11.440
But when Paul was talking, he recommended Prediction Machines and I recently finished

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:17.919
that book and that was heavy on there's kind of an economics twist with how do humans

00:10:17.919 --> 00:10:21.760
work in the future with algorithms as forecasting improves.

00:10:22.039 --> 00:10:26.039
So that's another, I think, really solid recommendation, Prediction Machines.

00:10:27.359 --> 00:10:32.840
Awesome. I went through a few of the recordings to write out some of the books that

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:38.520
have been mentioned in the past, and we are working on getting better at sharing all

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:40.840
this information that's being shared here.

00:10:41.159 --> 00:10:46.000
So I know someone had asked earlier, too, about how do we know like who's speaking

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:47.200
which week as well?

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.359
And we're working on creating a site for that so you can see all the resources shared

00:10:52.359 --> 00:10:53.440
and clips and stuff.

00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:55.039
So more to come on that.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:11:01.559
But there was an anonymous question, Jairus, around how did you get into data science

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:05.119
and what specifically attracted you to your current role?

00:11:05.919 --> 00:11:07.719
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:14.440
I guess I would say like I started in college that this would be the beginning of the

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:17.440
journey, like studying economics and mathematics.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:22.280
And it's funny, like you see a lot of data science concepts covered then, but they

00:11:22.280 --> 00:11:25.320
weren't branded as data science in school.

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:29.599
I guess we're behind on the branding when it comes to those things.

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.239
So I feel like I was picking up the techniques there.

00:11:32.239 --> 00:11:38.599
And my first role was in economic consulting, which is a very esoteric area.

00:11:38.599 --> 00:11:43.599
But it had to do with it was in the litigation space, companies suing companies,

00:11:43.599 --> 00:11:47.440
companies suing governments, governments suing companies and trying to understand like

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:52.479
what were the actual damages associated with wrongdoing and was there wrongdoing?

00:11:52.479 --> 00:11:55.039
And you could rely on econometric analysis to do that.

00:11:55.799 --> 00:11:58.039
But still, this is not this is not data science.

00:11:58.239 --> 00:12:01.960
And I think where I made the leap into data science was while I was doing that work,

00:12:02.919 --> 00:12:07.479
where I think I got most interested and motivated was was when I started learning how

00:12:07.479 --> 00:12:11.440
to do functions. I think that's where it really clicked for me of like you could write

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:15.919
a piece of code that makes your ability to do this in the future much, much easier and I

00:12:15.919 --> 00:12:17.039
can make my life easier.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:22.919
And I started to basically talk to friends who were who were going into data science

00:12:22.919 --> 00:12:27.159
from my network and realized like that is a space in which that sort of attitude gets

00:12:27.159 --> 00:12:29.880
rewarded. So it's like, OK, I'm interested in this.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:36.039
I'm excited by this. Let's start to find jobs that like like reward that, which I think

00:12:36.039 --> 00:12:37.520
is broadly the data science space.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:43.239
Right. So I made the jump into tech and started working on picking up the skills.

00:12:43.239 --> 00:12:46.320
And I've been really fortunate to have sort of a series of folks.

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:47.760
And this was a long time ago.

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:52.520
So I think it was easier to say like, hey, I know this language, but like I'll learn

00:12:52.559 --> 00:12:53.960
this one if you need me to.

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:58.799
And I had, you know, a few lucky breaks that enabled me to get where I am.

00:12:58.799 --> 00:13:01.320
And I'm obviously really appreciative of that.

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:02.919
So that's how I ended up in this space.

00:13:04.799 --> 00:13:06.080
That's awesome. Thank you.

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:11.320
I see there's a question early around hiring, too, and I know we wanted to dive deeper

00:13:11.599 --> 00:13:13.080
into this topic as well.

00:13:13.559 --> 00:13:17.119
Jairus was on an earlier webinar on hiring best practices.

00:13:18.039 --> 00:13:23.960
But the question was, what skill sets do you look for when hiring technically and also

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:25.159
personality wise?

00:13:25.479 --> 00:13:28.960
Yeah. Yeah, that's a it's a tough question.

00:13:30.719 --> 00:13:37.000
So I'm going to answer specifically for my team at Pandora what like what we do and

00:13:37.679 --> 00:13:38.919
hopefully this is helpful.

00:13:39.679 --> 00:13:44.320
Don't necessarily extrapolate this to like all of the data science ecosystem.

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:46.799
It's obviously very broad and people look for different things.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:53.359
But what I look for at the technical level is somebody has to be sort of like maybe

00:13:53.359 --> 00:13:54.919
facile is the best word.

00:13:54.919 --> 00:14:00.239
They have to be very comfortable with, I think, the common coding concepts that are

00:14:00.239 --> 00:14:01.479
going to pop up on the job.

00:14:01.479 --> 00:14:03.440
And I want them to sort of proactively motivate.

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:06.359
Right. I don't necessarily want to be the person that says, like, you should write a

00:14:06.359 --> 00:14:10.479
function here, right? Like the person should be comfortable enough with those concepts

00:14:10.479 --> 00:14:12.960
to sort of motivate them in their day to day work.

00:14:13.919 --> 00:14:19.919
On the personal side, what is tricky for us is that, you know, we end up working quite a

00:14:19.919 --> 00:14:24.799
bit with stakeholders and very early on when I hire people, I may have them in the room

00:14:24.799 --> 00:14:26.200
with stakeholders alone.

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:27.799
Like, obviously, I'm there to guide.

00:14:27.799 --> 00:14:31.760
But the ideal is to get them at the point where they're communicating well and

00:14:31.760 --> 00:14:33.880
presenting well, where they can handle that themselves.

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:41.280
And then they can also sort of scope the sorts of questions that they get or follow up

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:42.960
requests that they get from the stakeholders.

00:14:43.159 --> 00:14:46.719
So ideally, I want to get someone who says, OK, you know, I see you're asking for this,

00:14:46.919 --> 00:14:50.919
but if I understand your problem correctly, like I'd rather do this.

00:14:50.919 --> 00:14:53.239
I think this is actually the thing that's going to solve it for you.

00:14:53.840 --> 00:14:58.479
So people who are able to do that and what I've found is that you have folks who

00:14:58.479 --> 00:15:02.200
sometimes are very good at the technical side, but they're not as good at the other sort

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:04.280
of skills that we're looking for and vice versa.

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:08.599
So when we do our interviewing, we kind of try to emphasize both.

00:15:08.599 --> 00:15:12.320
And we understand that you're not going to be, you know, necessarily like 10 out of 10

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:16.039
on both. But we really do need a healthy balance because otherwise it's very difficult

00:15:16.039 --> 00:15:17.760
to sort of do what we do.

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:24.479
Other beneficial personality traits I look for in addition to communication are and this

00:15:24.479 --> 00:15:29.599
sort of comes out during the interview is interest in the sort of problems that we work

00:15:29.599 --> 00:15:32.719
on. I think it's really good to signal that during an interview.

00:15:33.719 --> 00:15:38.559
And what I found is that folks who do that during the interview process, you know, tend

00:15:38.559 --> 00:15:40.080
to continue to do it on the job.

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:41.960
I haven't seen very many good actors.

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:45.119
So when they're like, oh, you know, do you all look at this data or do you do that or

00:15:45.119 --> 00:15:46.119
have you thought about this?

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:50.559
Those folks tend to do very well in the role because they bring that sort of brainstorming

00:15:50.559 --> 00:15:52.080
mentality to the role.

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:56.239
And what I found is they're able to solve things in ways that, you know, I wouldn't have

00:15:56.239 --> 00:15:58.080
thought of. Other team members wouldn't have thought of.

00:15:58.080 --> 00:15:59.320
It really does help out a lot.

00:15:59.559 --> 00:16:04.039
So that's another thing that I look for versus the sort of passive applicant who's like,

00:16:04.039 --> 00:16:06.320
yeah, I don't know how to like, what do you guys do?

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:08.559
I'll just I'll just continue to sort of implement that.

00:16:10.919 --> 00:16:15.159
Definitely, I think that was a tip that you had mentioned in the webinar to just making

00:16:15.159 --> 00:16:20.960
sure to actually research the like field that you're in to make sure that you're aware

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:23.919
of what are the kinds of problems that they're facing.

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:29.080
Totally. Yeah, I'd say that's probably the most like common piece of advice.

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:31.719
I give folks I work with a boot camp as well.

00:16:31.719 --> 00:16:33.840
So I do calls with folks who are looking for jobs.

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:36.640
And then I had one yesterday just with a friend in my network.

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:41.479
And that's one of the things I say is like understand the business just because I mean,

00:16:41.479 --> 00:16:44.880
obviously it gives you stuff to talk about during the interview, you know, when it comes

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:46.159
to like small talk.

00:16:46.159 --> 00:16:50.559
But also like one of the most common data science questions I see is like, OK, what

00:16:50.559 --> 00:16:53.119
metrics would you look at if you were working here?

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:56.760
And a lot of folks are very caught off guard because they're like, I didn't realize I had

00:16:56.760 --> 00:16:58.599
to kind of solve that beforehand.

00:16:58.599 --> 00:17:01.599
Like I was hoping you would tell me and then we would do a problem on that.

00:17:01.799 --> 00:17:04.520
So I think it's nice to sort of bring that to the table.

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:08.119
And it makes any follow up questions a lot easier because you're already framing them

00:17:08.119 --> 00:17:10.839
in the context of, you know, the place you're applying.

00:17:12.719 --> 00:17:17.920
I really like that you said you put new hires into the room with the stakeholders as well

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:21.839
to like start that back and forth communication.

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:27.319
And I see there was a question that asked, how do you build confidence in communication

00:17:27.319 --> 00:17:29.599
and presentation skills within people?

00:17:30.479 --> 00:17:31.880
Yeah, so.

00:17:33.359 --> 00:17:39.199
What I would recommend is have like a mentor at your company, it doesn't have to be your

00:17:39.199 --> 00:17:45.040
manager, but somebody who has those skills and reach out to them and say, I would love

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:48.599
to go over a presentation with you or just invite them to your meeting.

00:17:48.599 --> 00:17:51.839
Sometimes that's a great way to to cheat at getting feedback.

00:17:51.839 --> 00:17:56.479
Oh, I need you. I need you in the room to see this, even though you may not necessarily.

00:17:56.680 --> 00:18:00.560
But someone who has those skills who can sort of guide you on it, because that's what I

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:06.239
try to do for my team, just having the I guess it came from the consulting background.

00:18:06.239 --> 00:18:10.520
I don't know where it came from, but wherever I picked it up, you know, I do think that's

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:11.880
one of the advantages I have.

00:18:11.880 --> 00:18:15.719
And of course, being in management, my technical skills have atrophied.

00:18:15.719 --> 00:18:17.959
So they're much better at that side of things.

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:23.760
But just the ability to make myself available and give them feedback before important

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:26.199
meetings or sit in the meetings and guide them.

00:18:26.199 --> 00:18:29.719
And then also give them the heads up that that's happening because not everyone likes to

00:18:29.719 --> 00:18:33.520
be caught off guard while say, OK, like, you know, let's move on to this topic because I

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:35.920
think someone's interested. Or can you explain that more?

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:37.040
I don't think everyone got it.

00:18:37.040 --> 00:18:41.839
Stuff like that. And over time, I think that reinforcement really helps out because

00:18:41.839 --> 00:18:44.760
eventually it's kind of like training wheels like you won't need them anymore.

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:48.959
You know, you've gotten enough practice with an advocate or a mentor that you can do it

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:53.959
yourself. I guess one thing to add on it is.

00:18:55.040 --> 00:19:00.680
Data scientists, I think, on average, tend to overestimate how much everyone else knows

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:05.119
about data science. So if you're like, am I over explaining it or under explaining it?

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:06.839
Odds are you're under explaining it.

00:19:06.839 --> 00:19:10.560
And again, depending on who's in the room, you know, again, we're thinking like

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:15.079
stakeholder management, folks who generally don't have a background in in the data side

00:19:15.079 --> 00:19:19.239
of things, I would err on the side of over explanation and then always give them an out.

00:19:19.239 --> 00:19:22.560
Right. You say, if you already know this or I'm being redundant, I will skip the slide or

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:24.520
skip this section and we can move on.

00:19:27.079 --> 00:19:32.560
That's really helpful, too, and just want to say again, if anybody wants to ask a

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:38.479
question live, Robert is teaching me to be a big proponent of the raising hand on

00:19:38.479 --> 00:19:39.959
Zoom as well.

00:19:39.959 --> 00:19:44.400
We're trying that in internal meetings or just unmuting yourself as well.

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:46.359
And I can take that as as raising your hand.

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:54.680
But, Ian, I see you had asked a question in the chat that you want me to read out, and it

00:19:54.680 --> 00:19:58.880
was, has the pandemic wreaked havoc with your time series models?

00:19:59.199 --> 00:20:04.839
Some weeks back, Elaine McVeigh discussed about how difficult time series modeling

00:20:04.839 --> 00:20:06.680
became in the CPG sector.

00:20:06.760 --> 00:20:08.560
Are you experiencing this as well?

00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:12.959
We did. Yeah, it's the effect is much more muted now.

00:20:12.959 --> 00:20:19.920
But at the beginning of the pandemic, there was, you know, a huge change in the way in

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:25.239
which people listen to Pandora that, of course, is now, you know, when extrapolated

00:20:25.239 --> 00:20:26.800
forward, having a lot of problems.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:33.599
So what I was kind of proud of was our team has, you know, the knowledge of how our

00:20:33.599 --> 00:20:36.560
algorithms work. Not only do we implement them, but we understand how they work.

00:20:36.560 --> 00:20:40.560
And we were able to very quickly identify, like, look, the outputs of these are not

00:20:40.560 --> 00:20:42.800
going to make sense. And so we had to sort of

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:48.640
pull alternative models online, which I think we did within two weeks or so, which I'm

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:49.760
pretty impressed by.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:54.319
And we, you know, we had probably some silly manual model we were using like in between

00:20:54.319 --> 00:20:56.800
then in order to account for it.

00:20:57.520 --> 00:21:00.280
But I was really proud of the way in which we sort of pivoted quickly.

00:21:00.280 --> 00:21:04.560
And I would say, like, if you're dealing with business side data, you should consider

00:21:04.560 --> 00:21:09.199
that a part of your job, because, again, there are folks who place a lot of emphasis on,

00:21:09.199 --> 00:21:12.319
you know, can I put these things into production and can I run them?

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:15.920
But if you're not making sure that they're resilient to things like this or you don't

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:20.560
have a plan for how you would fix it, I realize not everyone wants to plan like possible

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:24.319
pandemic into like every month of the work that they do.

00:21:24.319 --> 00:21:28.239
But if you don't have some way of pivoting quickly, you know, in the eyes of the folks

00:21:28.239 --> 00:21:31.040
you work for, they're like, wow, that person's like not really doing their job.

00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:33.599
And, you know, we pay them so much because they have all these skills.

00:21:33.599 --> 00:21:38.800
But like in some ways, you want to be resilient to these sorts of changes.

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:40.959
So I was really happy with how we dealt with it.

00:21:41.439 --> 00:21:47.760
It is still causing problems on models that our partner teams work on just because, you

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:51.680
know, we've decided we want to interpolate data and fill it in.

00:21:52.239 --> 00:21:56.800
But due to the nature of the structure, it's just like a lot to put there.

00:21:56.800 --> 00:22:01.280
And so we're trying to figure out, like, how much effort should we put into this sort of

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:06.239
interpolation and how much should we just sort of, you know, hand wave and maybe put

00:22:06.239 --> 00:22:09.760
less sophistication behind what we what we put in the historicals.

00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:11.599
But, yeah, it did affect us a lot.

00:22:12.319 --> 00:22:13.839
So great, great question, Ian.

00:22:17.839 --> 00:22:20.079
How do you know when your output wasn't making sense?

00:22:20.079 --> 00:22:21.520
Was it all accuracy metrics?

00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:24.800
Yeah, that's the way we determined it.

00:22:24.800 --> 00:22:30.000
And accuracy for us, you know, we have a good idea of how accurate like we should be and

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:31.839
then what's sort of abnormal.

00:22:31.839 --> 00:22:34.640
And we entered abnormality pretty quickly.

00:22:35.599 --> 00:22:41.040
So what I can tell you all about Pandora usage is like a lot of it we found is associated

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:42.000
with routine.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:46.719
And so when routines get disrupted, you see large changes in how people listen.

00:22:46.719 --> 00:22:50.479
And we saw that happening in March with shutdowns and with panic buying.

00:22:50.479 --> 00:22:55.760
You know, you're buying toilet paper, you may not remember to put on Pandora in your

00:22:55.760 --> 00:22:57.439
car when you're stressed out.

00:22:57.439 --> 00:22:59.280
So we did see that.

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:01.280
And, yeah, accuracy is what we use.

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:06.400
And it was just like this seasonal kink that, you know, you would not expect.

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:09.040
But for, you know, major disruption happening.

00:23:09.040 --> 00:23:11.119
So that's how we saw it.

00:23:12.079 --> 00:23:16.400
It was kind of interesting to see like it happened kind of at different places throughout

00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:16.880
the nation.

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:21.280
And we tried to line that up with sort of how serious folks were taking it.

00:23:21.839 --> 00:23:24.000
But at the end of the day, that was kind of acute analysis.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.199
There's nothing we can do with it.

00:23:25.199 --> 00:23:31.760
You know, where a really bad ongoing joke we had is like in that first two weeks, it

00:23:31.760 --> 00:23:35.439
was like, unless you're developing the vaccine, this is not going to change.

00:23:35.439 --> 00:23:39.280
So we need to just adapt sort of what we're looking at.

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:43.359
You know, we're not going to be able to do anything to sort of solve against this while

00:23:43.359 --> 00:23:46.000
people have much greater concerns on their minds.

00:23:49.119 --> 00:23:52.479
I know you mentioned the serious exam and Stitcher side as well.

00:23:52.479 --> 00:23:59.199
So I was curious, like being one big happy family, if the data science teams ever like

00:23:59.199 --> 00:24:01.920
work together, share insights as well.

00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:08.000
Like I was thinking with the pandemic, did people start listening to podcasts more versus

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:09.280
music at certain times?

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:16.400
Yeah, there were small changes in what people listen to.

00:24:16.400 --> 00:24:21.760
And the most obvious one is like health or news podcasts saw a spike.

00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:24.400
And it would have happened naturally.

00:24:24.400 --> 00:24:27.359
But also, obviously, like as a company, we started to promote those, right?

00:24:27.359 --> 00:24:29.199
We figured they were top of mind.

00:24:29.199 --> 00:24:34.160
So, you know, they did well, both by, I think, being relevant and by the company realizing.

00:24:34.160 --> 00:24:35.760
And this is, again, human in the loop, right?

00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:36.719
You need somebody.

00:24:37.599 --> 00:24:41.920
I believe it was a marketing led initiative to say, like, this is something that I think

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:43.040
is culturally relevant.

00:24:43.040 --> 00:24:44.079
People want to know about.

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:49.280
You know, the algorithm is not magically going to surface this podcast, which has not been

00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:50.800
as popular lately.

00:24:50.800 --> 00:24:55.760
And so they sort of pushed it in terms of like the type of music people listen to.

00:24:56.560 --> 00:25:00.959
We had a very honestly, I don't think the evidence was really good, but someone was

00:25:00.959 --> 00:25:04.160
definitely pushing the like people want to like they're panicky.

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:05.599
They want calming music.

00:25:05.599 --> 00:25:10.959
And so they were looking at like, oh, this like, you know, this calm genre that we have

00:25:10.959 --> 00:25:12.959
tagged is like increasing a little bit.

00:25:12.959 --> 00:25:17.280
But I don't know if I would have necessarily made that case.

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:21.199
It fit with the narrative of what was going on, but I'm not sure it was actually showing

00:25:21.199 --> 00:25:22.479
up or if it was just noise.

00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:25.439
Cool.

00:25:25.439 --> 00:25:25.920
Thank you.

00:25:26.959 --> 00:25:30.640
Fritz, I see you asked a question in the chat, and I'd love to turn it over to you to have

00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:32.079
you ask it live, if that's OK.

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:39.040
Or I could read it as well.

00:25:39.119 --> 00:25:42.079
So that always said you said you don't have a microphone.

00:25:42.079 --> 00:25:43.359
I'm happy to read it.

00:25:43.359 --> 00:25:47.839
The question was, what is the technological environment like at Pandora?

00:25:47.839 --> 00:25:50.160
How do you deploy models that your team develops?

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:57.520
Yeah, so we're on Google Cloud Platform for all of the sort of raw and upstream data that

00:25:57.520 --> 00:26:00.479
my team relies on and the data engineers get it there for us.

00:26:00.479 --> 00:26:06.560
So that's where we start working with Pandora data and we'll do aggregations there.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:08.000
You know, we have to handle ourselves.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:12.800
Sometimes logic needs to be applied to classifying various platforms.

00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:15.359
We don't want to deal with the laundry list that they have.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:22.319
So from there, we will get it into BigQuery or Postgres server we've just used for a long

00:26:22.319 --> 00:26:26.239
time and we've not migrated our jobs over to BigQuery.

00:26:26.239 --> 00:26:28.560
And then we'll connect to that with RStudio.

00:26:28.560 --> 00:26:34.400
So we're using RStudio either server for sort of the bigger projects that we have.

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:39.520
And then we'll use or if RS Connect is needed for a shiny dashboard and then sometimes a

00:26:39.520 --> 00:26:43.599
personal laptop just when it like doesn't really matter how much firepower you need.

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:49.760
So we'll use sort of both instances and personal can also be good for dev sometimes if you

00:26:49.760 --> 00:26:50.400
want to use it for that.

00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:55.439
And then for visualization or end product, you know, sometimes it's just dumping the

00:26:55.439 --> 00:26:58.880
data back into something like BigQuery or Postgres.

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:04.640
Sometimes it's, you know, a CSV that other folks in finance can ingest and use in Excel

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:08.479
or something that can be uploaded to Anna plan, which is how we manage a lot of our

00:27:08.479 --> 00:27:13.760
financial reporting or a shiny dashboard is what we sort of default to.

00:27:13.760 --> 00:27:15.920
And then we've inherited some work that's in Tableau.

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:17.119
So we'll do that as well.

00:27:17.839 --> 00:27:22.239
And what I would say is the way I like to explain it to stakeholders who are used to

00:27:22.239 --> 00:27:26.880
working with folks doing a lot of manual reporting is I say like one, you know, I'm

00:27:27.119 --> 00:27:33.680
reporting is I say like one or zero click to send this report to give them an idea of,

00:27:33.680 --> 00:27:37.280
you know, you may have folks putting together stuff in Excel and pulling manually from

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:38.239
different sources.

00:27:38.239 --> 00:27:42.400
We're able to sort of create this whole sort of pipeline or ecosystem for a lot of the

00:27:42.400 --> 00:27:46.239
problems that we do that require one click or zero clicks.

00:27:46.239 --> 00:27:50.079
The one clicks usually just to check to make sure everything makes sense before you send

00:27:50.079 --> 00:27:50.880
the report out.

00:27:53.119 --> 00:27:54.479
Yeah, so that's our ecosystem.

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:56.719
Thank you, Bruno.

00:27:56.719 --> 00:27:58.800
I see you had a question in the chat, too.

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:05.199
Can I pass the mic over to you in case people are tired of just hearing me talk and release?

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:13.680
I see you've unmuted, but we couldn't hear you yet.

00:28:13.680 --> 00:28:14.239
There you go.

00:28:14.239 --> 00:28:15.599
Yep, I'm here.

00:28:15.599 --> 00:28:16.239
Great.

00:28:16.239 --> 00:28:19.199
Hi, thanks for doing this question.

00:28:19.199 --> 00:28:23.280
From your experience, if you had to sell a data science project in an organization,

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:25.680
which is the most likely to succeed?

00:28:27.280 --> 00:28:34.479
An absolute baller presentation of result, but average predictive power, or an academic

00:28:34.479 --> 00:28:41.119
paper level long form presentation, you know, like no image, nothing, but now some predictive

00:28:41.119 --> 00:28:45.040
power, which has the most value to executives?

00:28:45.680 --> 00:28:48.079
Yeah, I'll kick it back to you, Bruno.

00:28:48.079 --> 00:28:52.640
So when you say to sell a data science project, do you mean something that's been created

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:54.319
and you're trying to get credit for it?

00:28:54.319 --> 00:28:57.439
Or it's like, here's something I want to go out and do?

00:28:58.479 --> 00:29:02.800
So say you build a team, you are your data scientist, because it's the buzzword of the

00:29:02.800 --> 00:29:03.359
week.

00:29:03.359 --> 00:29:06.719
And then the executive spent a lot of money to build this team.

00:29:06.719 --> 00:29:12.160
And then you come back with a result, let's say one or two years down the line, to justify

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:13.920
the reason for your existence.

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:14.640
Right.

00:29:14.640 --> 00:29:17.119
Does that makes a better context?

00:29:17.119 --> 00:29:17.920
Totally, yeah.

00:29:17.920 --> 00:29:21.439
So you've been doing a lot of projects during this time, and you want to communicate your

00:29:21.680 --> 00:29:24.160
the value of the business to them.

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:26.000
Okay, so I will answer your question.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.800
And then I'll take a sort of tangent related to that question.

00:29:29.839 --> 00:29:33.920
I would say like, the first thing is, it's dependent on who is the executive that you're

00:29:33.920 --> 00:29:34.880
presenting to.

00:29:34.880 --> 00:29:42.400
But by and large, at most companies, my experience has been the executives who hire or green

00:29:42.400 --> 00:29:46.640
light data science teams are not well versed in data science themselves.

00:29:46.959 --> 00:29:52.959
So a lot of I think the onus is on like management and leadership and data science to explain

00:29:52.959 --> 00:29:54.640
to them the value.

00:29:54.640 --> 00:30:00.239
And I think, you know, a good executive is not going to try and like pick you apart for

00:30:00.239 --> 00:30:04.400
not presenting stuff while they care about ultimately the bottom line, usually.

00:30:05.359 --> 00:30:11.599
So, you know, better results should work, but I think it's the way in which you frame

00:30:11.599 --> 00:30:12.160
them.

00:30:13.119 --> 00:30:17.280
So there's the idea of like making it pretty and making it impactful.

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:22.640
Pretty, you know, the iBankers are good at, the management consultants are good at, and

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:25.680
execs are used to working with them, and they're used to seeing things that way.

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:31.119
But if you were to do like a summary or output of a table that shows how much money you're

00:30:31.119 --> 00:30:35.119
saving the company through your optimization efforts, and that's in the millions of dollars,

00:30:36.160 --> 00:30:40.880
my hunch is that you don't really need to, you know, put that number in the same font

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:43.439
as everything else in the deck and make sure it's standardized.

00:30:43.439 --> 00:30:45.199
At the end of the day, I'd say that's what matters.

00:30:45.199 --> 00:30:50.640
So where I see sort of the, yeah, dollars speak, I saw you put in chat, where I see

00:30:50.640 --> 00:30:58.000
this sort of failure in like trying to show how good the data science team is or how much

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:02.880
they're doing is sometimes they will focus a lot on, you know, metrics that we're very

00:31:02.880 --> 00:31:05.040
comfortable with and are sort of easier to calculate.

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:08.640
And a classic example is we had a model that had 80% accuracy.

00:31:08.640 --> 00:31:10.079
I made it 84.

00:31:10.079 --> 00:31:15.119
But without doing some work to explain like what is the value of that to the business,

00:31:16.079 --> 00:31:18.239
you know, executives can sometimes be skeptical.

00:31:18.880 --> 00:31:21.280
Also, like they may not be well-versed in the problem space.

00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:24.400
So they might say 80 to 84, like that's not very good, right?

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:27.520
Like that doesn't seem like you did a very good job because they haven't been working

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:31.839
at those problems as long as you have and understand sort of the hairiness of them.

00:31:31.839 --> 00:31:36.800
So I guess more broadly than just dollars, I would say like speaking the language that

00:31:36.800 --> 00:31:38.560
they care about and are receptive to.

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:41.520
If you're in people analytics, it might be what are the things that we've done that

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:46.160
have resulted in employee retention, which again, ultimately makes its way down to dollars.

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:50.000
But make sure to coach it in like what they care about and what they're expecting.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:55.680
Because the way I like to view data science is, you know, at the end of the day, like

00:31:55.680 --> 00:31:57.599
they're hiring us because we have a skill set.

00:31:57.599 --> 00:32:00.800
It's a tool and it's a tool being applied to problems of the business.

00:32:00.800 --> 00:32:04.880
It doesn't matter how fancy your tool is if it's not solving the problems that the

00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:06.000
business has.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.959
So try to view it through their lens.

00:32:08.959 --> 00:32:13.599
You know, I've tried to do that throughout my career and I found, you know, that tends

00:32:13.599 --> 00:32:14.000
to work.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:15.040
That tends to work well.

00:32:19.040 --> 00:32:20.400
Thank you so much, Sharice.

00:32:20.400 --> 00:32:22.319
I'm marking to clip that one.

00:32:22.319 --> 00:32:25.199
I want to go back and share that.

00:32:25.199 --> 00:32:26.719
Yeah, edit appropriately.

00:32:26.719 --> 00:32:28.079
I know I was around.

00:32:28.079 --> 00:32:31.760
I was a little all over the place because I have strong feelings about it and it actually

00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:35.040
just reminded me of one additional thing and now I'm blanking on.

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:37.839
Maybe I'll remember it while we take the next.

00:32:37.839 --> 00:32:41.199
No, I mean, I mean, save that piece to share it with everybody.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:43.599
Yeah, that was incredibly helpful.

00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:50.640
There was a great question earlier that was, what are some small steps someone can take

00:32:50.640 --> 00:32:55.119
to become a more effective data scientist or leader in the long term?

00:32:55.920 --> 00:32:58.319
It seems like there's so much to learn and dive into.

00:32:59.040 --> 00:32:59.359
Yeah.

00:32:59.359 --> 00:33:05.199
So to be a leader, I'm going to think about that piece particularly.

00:33:05.199 --> 00:33:08.719
So like, what is the difference between a good data scientist and a good data science

00:33:08.719 --> 00:33:09.280
leader?

00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:12.160
And this relates a little bit to what Bruno was asking.

00:33:12.160 --> 00:33:19.040
So and I sort of had this as a rude awakening during my career, which was as a data scientist,

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:19.280
right?

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:23.199
A lot of emphasis is placed on like, what are the tools and techniques that you have?

00:33:23.199 --> 00:33:27.680
You know, why are they better than doing it manually or doing it under, you know, older

00:33:27.680 --> 00:33:30.640
styles of, say, like an Excel based report or what have you?

00:33:30.640 --> 00:33:33.599
Like, why do we need you and why do you do what you do?

00:33:33.599 --> 00:33:35.439
And so much emphasis was placed on that.

00:33:36.400 --> 00:33:39.680
But less so, you know, on the communication, my manager was handling it.

00:33:39.680 --> 00:33:42.239
And certainly on like project scope, right?

00:33:42.239 --> 00:33:46.719
It wasn't really my job to say, like, this project should entail this or it should do

00:33:46.719 --> 00:33:46.959
that.

00:33:46.959 --> 00:33:49.040
Or if we're trying to solve this problem, we should do this.

00:33:49.040 --> 00:33:52.160
Obviously, I was allowed to give some feedback, but ultimately, it wasn't my call.

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:58.959
Where I see like data science leadership, like what people who are doing well in that

00:33:58.959 --> 00:34:03.839
space, you know, the skills they have to develop and they may not be developing as an IC or

00:34:03.839 --> 00:34:09.360
obviously the communication presentation, being able to understand what are the needs

00:34:09.360 --> 00:34:15.040
of their stakeholders and then how can or cannot data solve those problems.

00:34:15.040 --> 00:34:18.080
So I say can, obviously, because that's the job.

00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:20.560
But can't is also really important as well.

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:24.080
Because if you have a stakeholder come to you and say, we want to train a model that

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:26.159
or can you build a model that does XYZ?

00:34:26.159 --> 00:34:27.280
Like, it's going to be great.

00:34:27.280 --> 00:34:30.879
And you say, yeah, I don't actually see how that's going to help the business.

00:34:30.879 --> 00:34:35.280
And you can sit down with them and explain why or say, historically, we've tried to

00:34:35.280 --> 00:34:37.439
develop models here and we haven't had much success.

00:34:37.439 --> 00:34:39.919
There's nothing I can think of that I think would do better.

00:34:39.919 --> 00:34:43.919
So instead of just sitting down and going and do that, you're the person who has some

00:34:43.919 --> 00:34:47.679
say around, you know, I think this is more likely to be successful and actually advance

00:34:47.679 --> 00:34:49.679
the needs of the business.

00:34:49.679 --> 00:34:53.360
And so, Rachel, that totally ties into what I was saying earlier, when you interview day

00:34:53.360 --> 00:34:57.840
one or day zero or negative one, depending how you look at it, if you understand the

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:03.600
business, I think it makes you much, much better able to do that than if you don't really

00:35:03.600 --> 00:35:04.879
know the inner workings of it.

00:35:04.879 --> 00:35:09.120
So the idea of proposing here are the projects I think are most likely to succeed and then

00:35:09.120 --> 00:35:10.560
getting people on board with that.

00:35:12.399 --> 00:35:16.959
Maybe this is a lazy analogy, but it almost feels somewhat like VC-like, like you're a

00:35:16.959 --> 00:35:18.159
data VC in some ways.

00:35:18.159 --> 00:35:22.080
Like I'm betting on these three projects to deliver value for the business and like I

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:27.520
need you to buy into them so I can have someone go out and do them and help us be sort of

00:35:27.520 --> 00:35:28.320
most successful.

00:35:32.080 --> 00:35:36.159
I really like explaining it that way, as being like a data VC.

00:35:37.679 --> 00:35:41.840
First, I see you just asked another question in the chat that I'll read out, which was

00:35:41.840 --> 00:35:45.840
how do you deal with people who feel a threat from machine models?

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:50.000
Those who are afraid of having their jobs displaced by data models.

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:53.280
Yeah, that's a tough one.

00:35:53.280 --> 00:36:01.360
I haven't had a ton of experience with that, but I would say right now the state we're

00:36:01.360 --> 00:36:10.959
at for a lot of sort of data informed projects at a company is that human in the loop is

00:36:10.959 --> 00:36:11.919
a great way to go.

00:36:11.919 --> 00:36:16.159
And if a human is in the loop, then you're not really threatening someone's job.

00:36:16.159 --> 00:36:20.800
The idea is I think that you are advancing the value that they offer because you're giving

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:24.800
them tools that they can use in order to do their job better.

00:36:25.679 --> 00:36:29.360
That is not always the case, so it's sort of dependent on how things are structured.

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:32.560
You can't tell someone, oh, it's human in the loop and then cut them out entirely.

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:36.879
But for a lot of things that we see, and I mentioned that example earlier where like

00:36:36.879 --> 00:36:41.840
we knew given the cultural climate and the global pandemic, people would be more interested

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:44.879
in health and news related to that than history.

00:36:44.879 --> 00:36:50.159
We need smart, good marketers to say, okay, I'm going to let the algorithms pick certain

00:36:50.159 --> 00:36:54.000
things to put in front of people, but I need to reserve this space for something that I

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:58.399
personally am willing to bet folks are really interested in or getting increased engagement.

00:36:58.399 --> 00:36:59.679
So that's how they work with it.

00:36:59.679 --> 00:37:02.000
I know I gave the Stitch Fix example earlier as well.

00:37:02.800 --> 00:37:04.639
Again, that's not always the case.

00:37:04.639 --> 00:37:08.159
It's kind of a cop out to say like, oh, everything will be human in the loop and we'll all be

00:37:08.159 --> 00:37:08.800
fine.

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:14.479
But in general, what happens with the progress we make on the machine side is that we kind

00:37:14.479 --> 00:37:19.600
of let people add more value because it's displacing sort of the easiest tasks.

00:37:19.600 --> 00:37:24.479
Again, this is on average, not always, but that's what I've been seeing, not just in

00:37:24.479 --> 00:37:26.399
my company, but at others as well.

00:37:26.399 --> 00:37:31.280
So I would say it's not so much threatening to your job as a whole, but it does mean that

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:35.520
if you're somebody who's been doing a job without a machine learning model, you need

00:37:35.520 --> 00:37:37.840
to understand how do I work with this thing?

00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:39.840
Because, you know, it's not going to go away.

00:37:42.399 --> 00:37:49.439
I know on previous weeks, we've also talked about the importance of testing and A-B testing

00:37:49.439 --> 00:37:54.639
and how sometimes we don't always do that or give it enough time to actually consider

00:37:54.639 --> 00:37:55.520
it a test.

00:37:55.520 --> 00:37:56.000
Yeah.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:02.879
And I'm just curious, like thinking of human in the loop project or aspect and having people

00:38:02.879 --> 00:38:07.919
recommend certain things like, oh, during the pandemic, people will look at health

00:38:08.879 --> 00:38:09.919
podcasts or something.

00:38:11.199 --> 00:38:16.239
How do you kind of push back if that's not actually the case or how do you test that

00:38:16.239 --> 00:38:18.320
out and have that conversation?

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:27.679
So the idea like is having a human, like someone intervening like better than the alternative.

00:38:28.479 --> 00:38:35.840
Or if somebody feels strongly that, for example, they're going to listen to health related

00:38:35.840 --> 00:38:40.000
things when that's not actually the case, how do you communicate that?

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:40.800
Gotcha.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:41.040
Yeah.

00:38:41.040 --> 00:38:45.120
So this is where we get into the fuzzy side of things very quickly, right?

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:51.199
Because when you have, you know, a well-behaved algorithm, a recommendation system, right?

00:38:51.199 --> 00:38:56.479
You can say with some confidence, like here's how much I expect people to like whatever

00:38:56.479 --> 00:38:57.360
content I'm giving them.

00:38:57.360 --> 00:39:02.560
We have a long history of how well this is done and we expect it to perform more or less

00:39:02.560 --> 00:39:04.399
just as well in the future, right?

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:09.199
And so when you have somebody, you know, a human saying, well, I want to change this

00:39:09.199 --> 00:39:13.199
or I want to change that, it really has to be done case by case because there's nothing

00:39:13.199 --> 00:39:17.360
in our framework that says, oh, you know, retune the algorithm, but for a pandemic,

00:39:17.360 --> 00:39:17.520
right?

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:19.760
We do not have the ability to do that.

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:23.360
So they really always get dealt on a case by case basis.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:28.639
But Rachel, you raise a really good point that I do know there are stakeholders who

00:39:28.639 --> 00:39:30.479
probably put too much.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:36.239
They put too much faith in the machines and they don't do enough of that.

00:39:36.239 --> 00:39:40.399
Alternatively, you have people who do the opposite, right?

00:39:40.399 --> 00:39:44.000
Who always want to override the machines and they do so to their own detriment.

00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:50.239
I'd say I agree with you that like A-B testing these approaches is a great idea to sort of

00:39:50.239 --> 00:39:54.479
create a historical record of like how good are our overrides.

00:39:54.479 --> 00:39:59.199
But the tricky thing about them sometimes is that you're not always able to do an A-B

00:39:59.199 --> 00:39:59.679
test.

00:39:59.679 --> 00:40:04.959
So you can't always actually figure out like what is the utility of, you know, having

00:40:04.959 --> 00:40:09.760
someone doing this intervention versus just letting the machine make its recommendations.

00:40:09.760 --> 00:40:12.159
But yeah, I would do it if possible.

00:40:12.159 --> 00:40:14.239
Sometimes it's tricky or not possible.

00:40:15.040 --> 00:40:18.800
But if it is possible, you can, what I would do is I would try to create a history of,

00:40:18.800 --> 00:40:21.600
you know, this person has tried to override recommendations.

00:40:21.600 --> 00:40:23.439
They did it in this period, in this period.

00:40:23.439 --> 00:40:26.879
And over time, they either, you know, batted above average or below average.

00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:31.760
And we can use that information to inform should we do more intervention in the future.

00:40:34.239 --> 00:40:35.120
That's really helpful.

00:40:35.120 --> 00:40:35.520
Thank you.

00:40:36.479 --> 00:40:40.000
See, there's a great question I had missed earlier.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:40.959
I'm just scrolling up.

00:40:41.840 --> 00:40:46.959
That was how do you advocate for the Pandora data team being involved in decision making?

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:48.399
Yeah.

00:40:48.399 --> 00:40:54.000
So this is where being in finance has been hugely beneficial.

00:40:54.639 --> 00:40:59.120
And I mentioned I was skeptical when I first joined because finance teams don't, you're

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:03.439
not generally associated with data prowess, no offense finance teams, or maybe offense

00:41:03.439 --> 00:41:03.760
taken.

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:06.639
So you all can, you know, go out and get better and prove me wrong.

00:41:08.080 --> 00:41:12.719
But being embedded in finance has helped with that hugely because at the end of the day,

00:41:12.719 --> 00:41:16.800
the decisions that we are making are coached in those terms, terms that everybody cares

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:20.080
about, obviously, the CFO and the CEO as well.

00:41:20.080 --> 00:41:25.760
And so once you've got that framing down of like, we're trying to understand how, you

00:41:25.760 --> 00:41:30.080
know, if this initiative, proposed initiative will be breakeven, or we want to understand

00:41:30.080 --> 00:41:37.040
what's the utility of missing our forecasts, like how bad is 1% miss and accuracy?

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:38.000
How bad is 2%?

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:41.199
Like, what are the downstream effects of making these mistakes?

00:41:42.719 --> 00:41:44.479
That has been hugely beneficial.

00:41:44.479 --> 00:41:48.879
So I also find that the finance problems are generally a little more well scoped.

00:41:48.879 --> 00:41:50.320
And this is for better or for worse.

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:54.000
It's just very easy to understand, like, yeah, we're doing breakeven on this or what

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:54.719
have you.

00:41:54.719 --> 00:41:58.879
It's a little trickier when it gets to someone like product where you say, well, we think

00:41:58.879 --> 00:41:59.679
we should build this.

00:41:59.679 --> 00:42:00.959
Do we have data to support it?

00:42:00.959 --> 00:42:04.320
You know, sometimes the answer is no, but you have to go out and build it anyways.

00:42:04.320 --> 00:42:10.000
So I would say the advocacy that I had to do over time was not me trying to convince

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:11.199
people of my team's worth.

00:42:11.199 --> 00:42:16.560
It was more just like producing, hopefully a drumbeat, constant drumbeat of wins and

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:20.000
then showing people like, look, this is what we do and how we do it.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.639
And you need to trust us and involve us in the process.

00:42:22.639 --> 00:42:27.520
And we've had times where folks have tried to go around us and try to sort of sell a

00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:29.360
decision without our involvement.

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:35.840
And, you know, our leaders have always backed us up and said, like, no, you need to involve,

00:42:35.840 --> 00:42:39.520
you know, this group or the finance team or the group within the finance team to make

00:42:39.520 --> 00:42:40.879
sure that that's the right decision.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:45.600
Awesome.

00:42:45.600 --> 00:42:46.080
Thank you.

00:42:46.639 --> 00:42:51.120
I just want to check that I haven't missed anyone's question yet so far and would love

00:42:51.120 --> 00:42:54.639
to have people unmute or come on live too.

00:42:58.080 --> 00:43:03.199
Yeah, I guess while you all are thinking, I might add, I do expect more organizations

00:43:03.199 --> 00:43:09.199
to start embedding data people in the finance org, or if there's like a hybrid org, right?

00:43:09.199 --> 00:43:11.919
So you have the data org where we're decentralized.

00:43:11.919 --> 00:43:15.919
But if you have the hybrid org, so data org, but everyone has sort of different groups

00:43:15.919 --> 00:43:22.080
that they support like dotted lines to ultimately that reporting into the CFO, I think is really

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:23.120
powerful.

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:27.120
And I've been seeing it more often just talking to folks in this space.

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:29.280
And I think that's going to become more popular.

00:43:29.280 --> 00:43:36.239
So Brian said in the chat backing up the finance team can be very helpful because there's

00:43:36.239 --> 00:43:36.959
power there.

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:41.679
I suspect going forward, you're going to have more and more finance teams looking to build

00:43:41.679 --> 00:43:42.879
out data folks under them.

00:43:45.679 --> 00:43:47.439
Robert, I see you have your hand raised.

00:43:47.439 --> 00:43:48.479
Can I turn it over to you?

00:43:49.120 --> 00:43:49.360
Yeah.

00:43:50.239 --> 00:43:51.280
Sorry, my camera's off.

00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:56.800
I'm getting a bite to eat, but great stuff so far on that topic.

00:43:56.800 --> 00:43:58.800
And this is something I've been thinking about personally.

00:43:58.800 --> 00:44:05.919
What should data scientists or really just anyone who doesn't work in a financial function,

00:44:05.919 --> 00:44:12.000
what are some basic things that they should understand about finance within a business

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:15.679
or assets that they should learn how to comfortably kind of look at?

00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:18.959
Yeah, that's a great question, Robert.

00:44:18.959 --> 00:44:21.520
I would say the basics will get you a long way.

00:44:21.520 --> 00:44:28.399
So revenue, cost, and then profit, which is sort of revenue minus cost.

00:44:29.520 --> 00:44:34.399
And then specifically, how does your company generate those revenues?

00:44:34.399 --> 00:44:37.280
How are those costs generated against those revenues?

00:44:37.280 --> 00:44:41.919
And then what are the ways in which your company is looking to sort of change over time or

00:44:41.919 --> 00:44:44.479
improve over time to improve those things?

00:44:44.479 --> 00:44:50.719
And then the last question that you can answer, right, is how can I use data to do that?

00:44:50.719 --> 00:44:52.719
And then that's you kind of doing the job.

00:44:52.719 --> 00:44:58.159
But it is interesting how many folks you talk to with a very strong data skill set who,

00:44:59.120 --> 00:45:02.800
you know, as I mentioned earlier, like, how do you put a value on accuracy improvement?

00:45:02.800 --> 00:45:07.040
So they've built their whole careers around, I'm going to learn models that can improve,

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:10.800
you know, the accuracy over whatever historical thing you were using.

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:12.879
And that's me doing a really good job.

00:45:12.879 --> 00:45:16.239
But in the eyes of the stakeholder, if there isn't someone to do the translation of, like,

00:45:16.239 --> 00:45:20.080
here's what those accuracy benefits mean in terms of dollars, and it doesn't have to be

00:45:20.080 --> 00:45:24.800
dollars today, it could be dollars tomorrow, it's really difficult to sort of make that

00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:26.560
case of what it's worth.

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:29.040
So those are the big ones, I would say.

00:45:29.120 --> 00:45:33.760
The thing I would add is, like, you don't need to go too far down the rabbit hole in

00:45:33.760 --> 00:45:39.120
terms of, like, for me, I guess it's on the margins, which is most important for us, right?

00:45:39.120 --> 00:45:43.840
So like the marginal revenue of doing something, the marginal cost, I have not spent a lot

00:45:43.840 --> 00:45:48.000
of time worrying about, like, how do you look at, like, headcount and finance against them?

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:49.840
Like, it's just not really a part of the job.

00:45:49.840 --> 00:45:53.840
And I think you can skip over that because it's not something you would be usually applying,

00:45:53.840 --> 00:45:56.879
you know, your data prowess to, but often it's on the margin.

00:45:56.879 --> 00:46:01.600
So you sell one additional product, or in our case, you get someone to listen, you know,

00:46:01.600 --> 00:46:04.560
10 additional hours on the ad supported tier, like, what does that work?

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:10.080
Thank you, Jairus.

00:46:10.080 --> 00:46:11.919
Bruno, I see you have your hand raised as well.

00:46:14.320 --> 00:46:17.040
Yeah, just to come back, second question.

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:23.360
What difficult part of your role would you rather a computer do instead of you?

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:28.159
So, you know, you allocate your time during the day, there's stuff that's enjoyable,

00:46:28.159 --> 00:46:30.479
there's other stuff that, you know, why I'm still doing this.

00:46:31.040 --> 00:46:35.439
So what is this part that the human process you find suboptimal?

00:46:36.239 --> 00:46:39.280
Okay, and is this something like in an ideal world?

00:46:39.280 --> 00:46:43.760
Or like, this is the next thing I'd want someone to go out and develop?

00:46:43.760 --> 00:46:45.520
Because those are very different answers.

00:46:45.520 --> 00:46:49.280
No, no, it's, yeah, ideal world, like the job of the future.

00:46:49.360 --> 00:46:50.320
The job of the future.

00:46:52.239 --> 00:46:53.520
Job of the future, yeah.

00:46:57.040 --> 00:47:04.399
What I would love for, and this is almost, this is goofy, but, you know, there's always more ideas

00:47:04.399 --> 00:47:10.320
than there is actual capacity to do work at an organization is what I've always found, you know,

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:14.639
and everybody loves to bring ideas to the table and say, hey, that, oh, I mentioned that a while

00:47:14.639 --> 00:47:16.080
ago, you know, like, I'm so great.

00:47:16.879 --> 00:47:20.879
But there's not that many people can actually sit down and implement them, right?

00:47:20.879 --> 00:47:22.479
You always have more ideas.

00:47:22.479 --> 00:47:29.840
So in an ideal world, I would love a little, like, email scraper to go through some of the

00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:34.879
suggestions I get and say something like, hey, we did that before and it didn't work.

00:47:34.879 --> 00:47:37.760
Or like, hey, we did that before and we're doing it right now.

00:47:37.760 --> 00:47:40.239
Like, that's not a new thing, it's already happening.

00:47:40.239 --> 00:47:42.080
Or that's a great idea, let's do that.

00:47:42.080 --> 00:47:46.159
And that that's a great idea will probably be 1% of the emails I get.

00:47:47.120 --> 00:47:50.719
But yeah, you know, it's the value of institutional knowledge.

00:47:50.719 --> 00:47:54.719
And you can argue once, you know, a computer does that, I would not have a job.

00:47:54.719 --> 00:47:58.080
But it is frustrating to say, like, yeah, that's how our things work.

00:47:58.080 --> 00:48:00.080
Or no, like, that's not possible.

00:48:00.879 --> 00:48:05.280
That sort of, you know, sorting of all the various initiatives that we get pitched,

00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:06.879
that would be nice.

00:48:06.879 --> 00:48:10.959
And I think there may be some low-hanging fruit because the same ideas do get recycled

00:48:10.959 --> 00:48:12.159
every few years.

00:48:12.159 --> 00:48:15.280
And so to just say, like, hey, you know, it's almost a Slack bot.

00:48:15.280 --> 00:48:16.320
Like, we tried that.

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:18.479
Like, check this wiki page on the results.

00:48:19.919 --> 00:48:21.360
I hope that wasn't too silly.

00:48:22.560 --> 00:48:23.679
I like that idea.

00:48:23.679 --> 00:48:27.760
Automatically taking it from your email, either putting it in your to-do list or not.

00:48:28.399 --> 00:48:29.360
Yeah, yeah.

00:48:30.080 --> 00:48:34.399
But especially for stuff that we've done or already tried, because people love to think

00:48:34.399 --> 00:48:38.080
that, like, oh, no one's thought of this before, I'm revolutionizing things.

00:48:38.080 --> 00:48:39.840
Like, no, we've done that before.

00:48:40.239 --> 00:48:43.840
It either worked and we continue to do it, or it didn't, and we're not going to do it

00:48:43.840 --> 00:48:44.080
again.

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:45.040
Yeah.

00:48:46.239 --> 00:48:47.919
Frank, I see you have your hand raised, too.

00:48:51.040 --> 00:48:52.080
Oh, you might be muted.

00:48:52.639 --> 00:48:52.959
All right.

00:48:54.800 --> 00:49:00.080
So, Jairus, I was just wondering, and maybe you mentioned this in your intro in the first

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:00.479
five minutes.

00:49:00.479 --> 00:49:01.520
If I missed it, I apologize.

00:49:01.520 --> 00:49:07.919
But do you have hobbies or passions outside of your data science work at Pandora that

00:49:07.919 --> 00:49:14.239
you use for creative ideas or inspirational thinking or just ways of looking at the world

00:49:14.239 --> 00:49:17.040
that you then apply back into your work?

00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:22.080
Yes, to the first half.

00:49:22.080 --> 00:49:26.159
I haven't quite figured out how I want to apply it yet, but I think the applications

00:49:26.159 --> 00:49:27.280
are there.

00:49:28.239 --> 00:49:35.199
And I guess I'll share a cute example of me doing an explore-exploit algorithm manually.

00:49:35.199 --> 00:49:36.159
So, I love cooking.

00:49:37.120 --> 00:49:39.439
And I'm cooking kind of nonstop.

00:49:40.639 --> 00:49:41.760
And so, I do it every day.

00:49:41.760 --> 00:49:44.080
Even if I'm really tired, I find energy for it.

00:49:44.080 --> 00:49:48.159
So, it's a very sticky hobby that I find really rewarding.

00:49:49.199 --> 00:49:52.959
And there are a lot of cooking analogies about the data science process.

00:49:52.959 --> 00:50:03.040
But for me, I think what has been most useful about understanding data or maybe technology

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:08.719
more broadly is there's all these sort of things in the cooking process that are kind

00:50:08.719 --> 00:50:09.919
of tweakable.

00:50:09.919 --> 00:50:16.320
And I personally think the modern way in which people interact with recipes doesn't really

00:50:16.320 --> 00:50:17.760
account for that.

00:50:17.760 --> 00:50:21.679
And so, what I've been playing on the side, and I don't know if this is a data thing or

00:50:21.679 --> 00:50:27.120
an app or something that I'm not smart enough to build, is how do you better represent that

00:50:27.120 --> 00:50:32.159
in a way that people who are either very good chefs or very good data people can better

00:50:32.159 --> 00:50:33.679
interact with the system?

00:50:33.679 --> 00:50:37.760
So, as an example, I'll give you is like I've tried a bunch of different ways of making

00:50:37.760 --> 00:50:38.879
the same recipe.

00:50:38.879 --> 00:50:43.760
But when you go to a website, you just see the one that someone did that they considered

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:44.399
to be best.

00:50:44.399 --> 00:50:48.159
And you don't really see information about how many things do they have to do to get

00:50:48.159 --> 00:50:48.639
here?

00:50:48.639 --> 00:50:51.040
And is there useful information about those things?

00:50:51.040 --> 00:50:57.919
Because if you read comments in recipes, a policy I have is read the most upvoted comment

00:50:57.919 --> 00:50:59.679
and do what that person says always.

00:50:59.840 --> 00:51:02.320
Your default should always be do what they say.

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:06.399
So, classically, you don't need that step or that's too much salt.

00:51:07.199 --> 00:51:12.000
Do what they say and then adjust the recipe because the recipe that gets posted on the

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:14.080
blog is often not final.

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:16.159
So, I like that a lot.

00:51:16.159 --> 00:51:20.879
And I'd love to just see the ecosystem get somewhere where I think it's accounting for

00:51:20.879 --> 00:51:23.199
the fact that everybody's kind of experimenting.

00:51:23.919 --> 00:51:27.360
So, in two years, if I'm working on a startup in stealth, that's what I'm doing.

00:51:27.360 --> 00:51:27.919
Now you know.

00:51:28.879 --> 00:51:31.120
But yeah, it's a good question.

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:36.719
I haven't been able to, I think, like draw tight enough connections with data.

00:51:36.719 --> 00:51:40.159
What I do recommend folks who are getting into this space to do is I say, you know,

00:51:40.159 --> 00:51:41.760
pick a project you're motivated about.

00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:44.159
And most people are motivated about their own data.

00:51:44.159 --> 00:51:48.080
So, the two areas I like to point them to are health and personal finance.

00:51:48.080 --> 00:51:51.120
Again, you have to have some prior interest in them.

00:51:51.120 --> 00:51:54.800
But those are great ones because it's like on the one hand, you know, do I want to muck

00:51:54.800 --> 00:51:58.719
around with an iris data set, even though I don't really know what an iris looks like?

00:51:58.719 --> 00:52:02.399
Or do I want to figure out where I'm overspending and can I predict future spend?

00:52:02.399 --> 00:52:05.280
Like, it's kind of, I think, a little more fun and exciting and tangible.

00:52:08.280 --> 00:52:09.919
I like how you flipped around, right?

00:52:09.919 --> 00:52:13.199
You're like, well, I use all these data science ideas and how I think about the data science

00:52:13.199 --> 00:52:16.239
rather than apply it to my passions to get better at my passions.

00:52:16.239 --> 00:52:16.739
Yeah.

00:52:17.600 --> 00:52:17.840
Yeah.

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:20.719
So, maybe it's just like the overarching style of thinking.

00:52:20.719 --> 00:52:21.219
Yeah.

00:52:21.679 --> 00:52:23.600
Hugh says GitHub for recipes.

00:52:23.600 --> 00:52:24.560
Yes, Hugh.

00:52:24.560 --> 00:52:26.239
That's what I'm going for, basically.

00:52:27.120 --> 00:52:28.000
So, stay tuned.

00:52:29.760 --> 00:52:30.479
Awesome.

00:52:30.479 --> 00:52:33.520
I see Libby had asked a question in the chat, too.

00:52:34.239 --> 00:52:39.439
That was, do you find it more beneficial to hire generalists or specialists when a team

00:52:39.439 --> 00:52:41.600
is first being built for a new project?

00:52:43.679 --> 00:52:44.959
Yeah, good question, Libby.

00:52:45.919 --> 00:52:48.879
My experience is generalists.

00:52:48.879 --> 00:52:56.000
But again, that's me as a leader saying I know that I am often unable to predict what

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:57.760
future needs of the team will be.

00:52:59.040 --> 00:53:05.600
And in order to accept that, you can't hire specialists because if they're specialized

00:53:05.600 --> 00:53:10.560
in an area that gets de-emphasized or something, they're not going to be as good of a fit as

00:53:10.560 --> 00:53:12.239
someone who's a generalist.

00:53:12.239 --> 00:53:14.479
So, my team hires generalists.

00:53:14.479 --> 00:53:16.320
Obviously, it's team dependent.

00:53:16.879 --> 00:53:20.879
But I mentioned before, right, we don't expect you to be 10 out of 10 in any specific thing,

00:53:20.879 --> 00:53:24.719
but you need to be like seven or eight on a bunch of things because you are going to

00:53:24.719 --> 00:53:28.399
get pulled in different directions and sort of have to do different parts of projects.

00:53:29.439 --> 00:53:29.939
Yeah.

00:53:33.520 --> 00:53:34.080
Awesome.

00:53:34.080 --> 00:53:34.719
Thank you.

00:53:35.520 --> 00:53:37.360
Rick, I see you have your hand raised as well.

00:53:37.360 --> 00:53:38.320
Can I turn it over to you?

00:53:39.439 --> 00:53:40.399
Thanks, Rachel.

00:53:40.399 --> 00:53:42.159
A really great conversation so far.

00:53:42.159 --> 00:53:46.080
I had a couple of points I wanted to mention, but one thing that I wanted to jump in on

00:53:46.080 --> 00:53:51.199
was this idea of the cooking and the data algorithms.

00:53:51.199 --> 00:53:55.120
And I'm a biologist, and we use the same analogy all the time that working in the

00:53:55.120 --> 00:53:59.520
laboratory and doing experiments and mixing reagents is just like being in the kitchen

00:53:59.520 --> 00:54:00.399
at home.

00:54:00.399 --> 00:54:06.399
But I think the difference is that at home, when you cook, when you read a cookbook, people

00:54:06.399 --> 00:54:11.120
don't know why there is salt or what's the difference between baking powder and baking

00:54:11.120 --> 00:54:14.800
soda, for example, or how the humidity in the air affects what you're cooking.

00:54:14.800 --> 00:54:18.800
But in the laboratory, you know every single reagent and you know exactly how the concentration

00:54:18.800 --> 00:54:20.719
is going to affect the outcome of your experiment.

00:54:20.719 --> 00:54:22.879
So why do I put this much magnesium in?

00:54:23.760 --> 00:54:24.399
What is it doing?

00:54:24.399 --> 00:54:25.120
What is EDTA?

00:54:25.120 --> 00:54:26.320
And what are all these chemicals?

00:54:26.320 --> 00:54:30.320
And I think it's a similar thing with data scientists that they look at, OK, just get

00:54:30.320 --> 00:54:35.040
an answer and just focus on this metric and how everything is connected and the pulleys

00:54:35.040 --> 00:54:35.919
under the hood.

00:54:35.919 --> 00:54:38.159
Like, if I increase this, how does that affect the result?

00:54:38.159 --> 00:54:39.199
I don't think that's played.

00:54:39.280 --> 00:54:42.879
I mean, my impression, at least, is that I don't think it's been played enough around

00:54:42.879 --> 00:54:44.080
with when people are learning.

00:54:44.080 --> 00:54:48.159
They just learn the ropes and they don't learn to be playful and really experiment and see

00:54:48.159 --> 00:54:51.040
how those things do, how these affect the results.

00:54:51.040 --> 00:54:55.679
So like when I teach stuff, I try and make a simulation, like make a shiny app that allows

00:54:55.679 --> 00:54:58.560
people to just simulate some data.

00:54:58.560 --> 00:55:00.399
And what if I had this in my data?

00:55:00.399 --> 00:55:01.439
What if I had this distribution?

00:55:01.439 --> 00:55:03.360
What if I change this parameter?

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:06.879
How does that affect the output at the end to get a more intuitive feeling?

00:55:06.879 --> 00:55:08.800
Do you think that would be something that can work?

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:11.760
I think it would work for cookie as well as well, actually.

00:55:11.760 --> 00:55:12.959
Yeah, that.

00:55:12.959 --> 00:55:14.239
So that's a great suggestion.

00:55:15.199 --> 00:55:19.919
I have someone on my team who is really good at that style of thinking, and I am notoriously

00:55:19.919 --> 00:55:20.479
bad at it.

00:55:21.040 --> 00:55:25.120
And the reason I'm bad at it, and maybe it's a good thing, is that, like, if you chase

00:55:25.120 --> 00:55:28.959
down all those things, like many of them don't work or are not beneficial.

00:55:29.520 --> 00:55:33.040
And in my the way my mind works is like, oh, you're going to waste your time, like, you

00:55:33.040 --> 00:55:34.800
know, 2% chance that'll make sense.

00:55:35.439 --> 00:55:39.520
But I think it's really important to have folks on the team who do have those skills.

00:55:39.520 --> 00:55:44.159
So, like, we kind of compliment each other because she'll come up with a lot of suggestions

00:55:44.159 --> 00:55:49.439
and I'll say, OK, of the 40 you just said in two minutes, let's do like 10 of those.

00:55:49.439 --> 00:55:51.679
But these are the 10 I think I have the most faith in.

00:55:52.479 --> 00:55:57.600
But I do think that playfulness is really important on the job or just the creativity

00:55:57.600 --> 00:55:58.159
in general.

00:55:59.040 --> 00:56:02.320
Because as you mentioned, right, you do see people who are just like, just get the metric,

00:56:02.320 --> 00:56:03.360
just get the answer.

00:56:03.439 --> 00:56:08.239
And I think if you're not understanding how it fits into the greater whole, right, again,

00:56:08.239 --> 00:56:11.439
understand the business, understand your role in the business and what you're trying to

00:56:11.439 --> 00:56:13.439
do, you're not you're not going to be successful.

00:56:14.560 --> 00:56:19.439
You know, again, I like analogies like, would you rather have a precise cupcake or a delicious

00:56:19.439 --> 00:56:20.000
cupcake?

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:20.239
Right.

00:56:20.239 --> 00:56:22.239
I think I think we all know which one we prefer.

00:56:23.439 --> 00:56:23.939
Yeah.

00:56:25.120 --> 00:56:29.760
I think what Rick's getting at is that's the scientist part of data scientist.

00:56:30.479 --> 00:56:33.199
And we call them that for two reasons.

00:56:33.199 --> 00:56:35.760
There is an element of science and experimentation.

00:56:37.679 --> 00:56:41.040
And I think what's often left out of the picture is hypothesis testing.

00:56:41.040 --> 00:56:46.000
And, you know, everybody wants to throw out all the statistics and just go to some auto

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:47.120
ML and be done with it.

00:56:47.120 --> 00:56:53.120
And it's kind of like, well, you got to have some reasonable hypothesis before you get

00:56:53.120 --> 00:56:53.679
started.

00:56:53.679 --> 00:56:58.159
Otherwise, you will, as you say, Jared, you're going to wind up going down these rabbit holes

00:56:58.159 --> 00:57:00.320
and two percent loops and everything else.

00:57:00.320 --> 00:57:03.760
And I think that's because my background is in chemistry, too.

00:57:03.760 --> 00:57:06.000
And I was involved in making materials and stuff.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:08.000
So it's just like cooking.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:09.520
There is that creative element.

00:57:09.520 --> 00:57:12.320
But it's the same thing with data science modeling.

00:57:12.320 --> 00:57:15.760
Like, you know, how do we get it a little bit better?

00:57:15.760 --> 00:57:19.600
Or what can we learn from this last model to make the next one better?

00:57:19.919 --> 00:57:29.679
I know we're getting to the top of the hour here, but I love this discussion that's going

00:57:29.679 --> 00:57:29.919
on.

00:57:29.919 --> 00:57:35.120
So if anybody has time to stay on, definitely stay here with us.

00:57:35.840 --> 00:57:38.879
But, Jairus, I also want to be respectful of your time.

00:57:38.879 --> 00:57:41.600
And I don't know if you have a meeting to run to right after.

00:57:43.840 --> 00:57:44.719
I don't know either.

00:57:46.080 --> 00:57:47.520
I'm going to check real quick.

00:57:48.479 --> 00:57:54.399
But, yeah, if anyone has any other cooking or data related things they want to mention,

00:57:54.399 --> 00:57:55.679
let me just check real quick.

00:57:57.280 --> 00:58:02.320
There's a few questions still coming through from Slido, too.

00:58:02.320 --> 00:58:05.840
So I'll just ask one quick one.

00:58:07.040 --> 00:58:09.840
Someone said, totally out of context, but would be a big help.

00:58:09.840 --> 00:58:12.000
Does Pandora sponsor work visas?

00:58:13.439 --> 00:58:14.320
I don't know.

00:58:14.320 --> 00:58:15.040
I'm sorry.

00:58:15.040 --> 00:58:15.840
I wish I did.

00:58:15.840 --> 00:58:17.600
I should have that information handy.

00:58:18.639 --> 00:58:22.639
But if you are interested in a role, feel free to reach out on the side.

00:58:22.639 --> 00:58:23.760
Yeah, it's on LinkedIn.

00:58:23.760 --> 00:58:24.800
I can look into it for you.

00:58:26.399 --> 00:58:27.040
Awesome.

00:58:27.040 --> 00:58:31.840
And, Hugh, I see you had also asked a question earlier, if you want to jump in and ask that

00:58:31.840 --> 00:58:32.560
one.

00:58:32.560 --> 00:58:33.280
Yeah, sure thing.

00:58:34.080 --> 00:58:37.280
So you had mentioned a little while ago about kind of chasing some of the stuff you're

00:58:37.280 --> 00:58:42.560
interested in, like cooking or at work, making time to focus on something you're interested

00:58:42.560 --> 00:58:44.320
in rather than the day-to-day work.

00:58:45.120 --> 00:58:50.159
I was just curious, have you noticed that paying longer term dividend or paying more

00:58:50.159 --> 00:58:54.239
dividends in the long term by kind of chasing your interest or your passion rather than

00:58:54.239 --> 00:58:55.520
that work that's right in front of you?

00:58:58.800 --> 00:59:02.560
Yeah, so I guess in a world in which, like, I'm trading off, like, do I want to spend

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:06.800
some time in the kitchen or do I want to do more studying or more work or something?

00:59:08.239 --> 00:59:13.360
Yeah, I would say, like, for my happiness and I think for everyone's happiness, I think

00:59:13.360 --> 00:59:17.760
it's important to do things that you care about and also recognize that even if you

00:59:17.760 --> 00:59:21.439
care very deeply about something, it may not be healthy to do it all the time.

00:59:22.239 --> 00:59:24.000
So there are folks I've seen.

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:28.879
I have one friend in the data space who loves it, and it seems like if 100 percent of his

00:59:28.879 --> 00:59:32.800
time were dedicated to it, he would be the happiest clam in the entire ocean.

00:59:32.800 --> 00:59:35.600
But most people aren't like that, and I think that's fair to recognize.

00:59:36.479 --> 00:59:40.239
You know, when I do cook, I'm not always doing it with the lens of, like, how does

00:59:40.239 --> 00:59:41.520
this help me in the data world?

00:59:41.520 --> 00:59:46.159
But I think I pull, like, sort of my knowledge of the data world to the way in which I approach

00:59:46.159 --> 00:59:47.760
my cooking, which is helpful.

00:59:48.639 --> 00:59:51.199
Yeah, at the end of the day, I would say feed your soul.

00:59:51.199 --> 00:59:54.879
And if you know what your soul wants, go do that.

00:59:54.879 --> 00:59:57.679
And if you don't know what your soul wants, try and figure it out.

00:59:57.679 --> 00:59:58.239
Experiment.

00:59:59.040 --> 01:00:01.840
But yeah, I don't think I could do the alternative.

01:00:01.840 --> 01:00:03.520
I'd be very unpleasant to be around.

01:00:05.040 --> 01:00:05.439
Thank you.

01:00:06.399 --> 01:00:09.520
I was thinking more in the context of a work environment, too.

01:00:10.399 --> 01:00:13.840
I'm supposed to be working on forecasts for something.

01:00:13.840 --> 01:00:15.120
You know, that's my long term.

01:00:15.120 --> 01:00:16.320
You know, that's my current task.

01:00:16.320 --> 01:00:22.159
But I'm really more interested in chasing deep diving into graph databases or something

01:00:22.159 --> 01:00:23.679
else where I have an interest.

01:00:23.679 --> 01:00:30.000
And really, you know, like, long term, that ends up, you know, paying much more dividends

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:33.280
than if I just chased kind of the work that's directly in front of me.

01:00:33.280 --> 01:00:34.000
Got it.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:37.199
Sorry, I didn't do a good job of asking earlier.

01:00:37.199 --> 01:00:38.080
No, no, of course.

01:00:38.080 --> 01:00:38.800
No, thank you.

01:00:39.040 --> 01:00:39.760
That's helpful.

01:00:39.760 --> 01:00:45.760
So I guess it's the context that like you want to do the stuff you're passionate about

01:00:45.760 --> 01:00:48.399
to eventually get like a role in that area.

01:00:52.399 --> 01:00:56.959
Let's get a role in more, you know, chase your interest at work.

01:00:58.080 --> 01:01:04.719
And rather than necessarily just doing exactly that kind of this is exactly what I'm supposed

01:01:04.719 --> 01:01:05.280
to be doing.

01:01:05.280 --> 01:01:07.120
This is the task I'm assigned to.

01:01:07.120 --> 01:01:08.479
You have to do a certain amount of that.

01:01:08.479 --> 01:01:10.239
But exploring your interest as well.

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:15.280
Long term and kind of chasing some of those things you're really curious or passionate

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:21.199
about and bringing those into the work that you do to kind of see the payoff there.

01:01:21.199 --> 01:01:22.159
Or do you see a payoff?

01:01:23.199 --> 01:01:24.239
Yeah, totally.

01:01:24.239 --> 01:01:27.600
So the way I've seen, I have not been great at this myself.

01:01:27.600 --> 01:01:32.399
But the way I've seen people who do this well is one, they do the core job and they do it

01:01:32.399 --> 01:01:37.280
well and they understand sort of what's me doing a good job or is a great job or is an

01:01:37.280 --> 01:01:38.159
amazing job.

01:01:38.159 --> 01:01:41.600
And they're generally smart enough people to pick where on that spectrum they want to

01:01:41.600 --> 01:01:42.320
be.

01:01:42.320 --> 01:01:43.919
So these are usually very bright people.

01:01:43.919 --> 01:01:47.360
And they say, I could do an amazing job, but I'm just going to do a good job.

01:01:47.360 --> 01:01:52.320
And then I'm going to invest that remaining 20% of my time or whatever it is into stuff

01:01:52.320 --> 01:01:53.280
I care about.

01:01:53.280 --> 01:01:57.120
And I'm going to do it in a way that I can sort of spin to my manager or leadership is

01:01:57.120 --> 01:01:58.320
like this has potential.

01:01:58.320 --> 01:01:59.520
We should look into it.

01:01:59.520 --> 01:02:04.239
And when you do that and you're doing a good job, I found it sort of rare for someone to

01:02:04.239 --> 01:02:07.120
say like, no, I don't want you doing that, right?

01:02:07.120 --> 01:02:08.800
Because you might leave.

01:02:08.800 --> 01:02:11.199
And now they have someone not doing a good job.

01:02:11.199 --> 01:02:16.159
So I found that that's the way to sort of make it like politically palatable is to say

01:02:16.159 --> 01:02:18.479
like, look, I'm already doing all the stuff I need to do.

01:02:18.479 --> 01:02:20.879
But here's where I want to sink some extra time into.

01:02:21.840 --> 01:02:26.560
And then you kind of coach it in a way that like is useful to them.

01:02:26.560 --> 01:02:29.120
So research and testing gets thrown around a lot.

01:02:29.120 --> 01:02:30.479
I want to research these techniques.

01:02:30.479 --> 01:02:31.919
I think they might be helpful.

01:02:31.919 --> 01:02:34.479
If you're doing a good job, it's usually easy to sell.

01:02:34.479 --> 01:02:37.679
If you're not doing a good job at your work, it's harder to say, well, I want to try this

01:02:37.679 --> 01:02:38.800
and I want to try that.

01:02:38.800 --> 01:02:44.080
So I found the folks who are really good are folks who, again, they're kind of picking

01:02:44.080 --> 01:02:46.399
the level of effort on the core responsibilities.

01:02:46.399 --> 01:02:49.600
And then they're just coming up with a decent pitch for the stuff they're passionate about

01:02:49.600 --> 01:02:51.600
and just tying it to the business in some way.

01:02:51.600 --> 01:02:53.919
Awesome.

01:02:53.919 --> 01:02:54.320
Thank you.

01:02:55.280 --> 01:02:56.000
That's incredible.

01:02:56.959 --> 01:02:59.919
We used to use the 80-20 rule at a place that I worked at.

01:02:59.919 --> 01:03:02.639
And I was able to sell it to the other management.

01:03:02.639 --> 01:03:07.679
It was like 80% of our work is going to keep the lights on and keep the business going.

01:03:07.679 --> 01:03:12.399
But 20% of the work is going to be on what is the next thing down the road that it's

01:03:12.399 --> 01:03:12.800
going to be.

01:03:14.719 --> 01:03:17.919
And understanding that that's a long-term investment.

01:03:19.280 --> 01:03:22.800
And it could be as simple as like when I was working with some of my junior data scientists,

01:03:23.520 --> 01:03:26.479
I'm going to take a course in deep learning for this.

01:03:27.360 --> 01:03:30.479
Granted, we're not using that in the group today and everything else, but we might need

01:03:30.479 --> 01:03:31.280
it down the road.

01:03:31.280 --> 01:03:32.239
And that's an investment.

01:03:33.520 --> 01:03:36.879
And I think as a leader, you have to encourage that.

01:03:36.879 --> 01:03:40.320
And it can't be you only do it on nights and weekends on your own time.

01:03:41.919 --> 01:03:44.800
And so I used to have an expression is Friday is my day.

01:03:46.080 --> 01:03:48.800
And so I would pitch that to my team members.

01:03:48.800 --> 01:03:51.520
Friday is your day to do something new.

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:53.120
You just need to tell me what you're doing.

01:03:53.120 --> 01:03:55.199
And obviously, we got to keep the lights on too.

01:03:55.199 --> 01:03:58.320
And you'll know that pretty quickly if the lights aren't being kept on.

01:03:59.600 --> 01:04:05.199
But it's a way to orient people to grow themselves.

01:04:05.199 --> 01:04:06.879
Otherwise, it just never happens.

01:04:07.679 --> 01:04:14.320
Or you force people to do it on their own, which is now you're just putting all the learning

01:04:14.320 --> 01:04:14.800
on them.

01:04:14.800 --> 01:04:19.439
And as a leader or as an organization, you expect to take everything from them and not

01:04:19.439 --> 01:04:20.399
give them anything back.

01:04:20.399 --> 01:04:23.360
And that doesn't really help people grow either.

01:04:27.840 --> 01:04:28.800
Yeah, that's great, Brian.

01:04:28.800 --> 01:04:30.320
I think formally carving it out.

01:04:30.320 --> 01:04:32.320
And I think that was also a Google thing, right?

01:04:32.320 --> 01:04:35.360
Like 20% time is the best way to go.

01:04:35.360 --> 01:04:37.520
I have not been successful in being able to do that.

01:04:37.520 --> 01:04:41.679
But I think it's the nature of sometimes we get requests that are urgent.

01:04:41.679 --> 01:04:44.000
And you can't say like, this is my time.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:48.320
But as a result, I think we've done a lot of the automation to make sort of what could

01:04:48.320 --> 01:04:51.760
take X hours is now maybe even X over two.

01:04:51.760 --> 01:04:55.199
And so that frees up a lot of space for other stuff that we work on.

01:04:55.919 --> 01:04:59.040
And at the end of the day, I think the pitch is important.

01:04:59.040 --> 01:05:02.080
So you say, someone on my team wants to learn XYZ.

01:05:02.080 --> 01:05:03.600
Here's the ways in which it could be helpful.

01:05:03.600 --> 01:05:07.520
And again, if you're doing generally well in your role, leadership's usually happy to

01:05:07.520 --> 01:05:08.639
just say, yeah, go for it.

01:05:09.199 --> 01:05:09.760
Yep.

01:05:09.760 --> 01:05:12.159
And I understand you're in finance.

01:05:12.159 --> 01:05:13.760
And I've worked in finance and everything else.

01:05:13.760 --> 01:05:17.520
And the other way I tell people to look at it is you can't do that.

01:05:18.159 --> 01:05:22.239
Spend your first half hour of the day doing it.

01:05:22.239 --> 01:05:26.959
So five days a week, if you work from 8 to 8.30, you check your emails, make sure the

01:05:26.959 --> 01:05:29.600
building's not burning down, the whole organization isn't in flames.

01:05:30.159 --> 01:05:32.479
And then you work for a half hour on this little project.

01:05:32.479 --> 01:05:33.360
That's it.

01:05:33.360 --> 01:05:35.840
The end of a week, you've done two and a half hours.

01:05:35.840 --> 01:05:38.239
Or at the end of two weeks, you've done a lot.

01:05:38.239 --> 01:05:44.239
And then it's that little bit of work goes a long way over a period of time too.

01:05:44.320 --> 01:05:47.760
And you're not really interfering with the works at all.

01:05:48.879 --> 01:05:50.399
And I try to tell people to do that also.

01:05:50.959 --> 01:05:54.080
If you can't, if we don't have time or anything else, do that.

01:05:54.719 --> 01:05:59.360
That's the first thing you should do before you even do anything else is grow a little

01:05:59.360 --> 01:05:59.860
bit.

01:06:01.679 --> 01:06:02.399
Yeah, I love that.

01:06:02.399 --> 01:06:03.760
I love putting it first too.

01:06:05.760 --> 01:06:09.679
Yeah, I used to have other hobbies that I would try to do, mostly failing.

01:06:09.679 --> 01:06:12.320
But I would try to do it at the beginning of the day because you always have energy

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:13.199
at the beginning of the day.

